Text: I was planning to complete the excavation before working on the above parts.With all the rain & how slow it will drain out through the few cracks, I think tomorrow I'll try to get the basic framing done. Then I can put up a tarp & limit any more water from being added.

So we had to wrap before we finished the story, but we had a wrap-up session before everyone got slammed with professorships and vet school. I got to tell them what they were missing out on and answer questions. It was amazing! Not a bad first go tbh; 12/12 https://t.co/xolSFJRzw6

Another major highlight was that I had a bout of writer's block, so I hopped on @cconowitch's Ko-Fi, and she masterfully filled that part in for me (and helped with a lot of other stuff too!). 10/10 would recommend! I also got to use @FantasyEcology's Hell Swarm, which I loved.

I also didn't have a proper backstory for an important story element, so I designed a smaller campaign around it and let 4 other brand-new D&D players write it for me by being the party in the story. Wrapped everything up in a tight little bow for me! They are on Session 11 now.

Favorite mechanic I wrote in was an army of Sand Golems moving about the map that would sack cities based on their time spent on side quests. They had no idea it was happening and it had a pretty big impact on the story.

Anyway, highlights! Favorite NPC was CL3R1C (called Claire): a solar-powered warforged druid who ran a sun-worshiping temple. Favorite magic item I made: Bag of Hole-ding, a BoH they got in a joke shop that slips their stuff btw/ pocket dimensions based on rolls.

The players, 2 brand new to D&D and two who had played before, will average 1 PhD-level degree each once our Rogue wraps her DVM/PhD program. The DM does not have a PhD, but was in charge anyway. Who wasted whose time now?? It was an amazing group.

It was an island surrounded by impassable magic sand with lots of history for the players to largely ignore at their leisure. Storm sorcerers I called the Engineers were responsible for maintaining storms and keeping the river flowing (ecosystem engineers? anyone?). https://t.co/1vQM5fcIdm

I'd never built a map before, so I turned to my usual muse for creativity: beer. The outline was beer foam and the features were more different beer foam. I inverted them, superimposed, and used @inkarnaterpg to turn it into a real fake place. https://t.co/FQd9Wvhw7t

So imagine a young, gray-skinned Aasimar woman with a frilly green dress and a Solar at her side (which had to modify because the party wasn't nearly high enough level for one, but I liked the joke). Then I built the world around her!

Like the eastern emerald elysia, Elyse drew her power from the sun. Through a process called kleptoplasty, E. chlorotica incorporates chloroplasts from some of the algae, etc. it eats and can properly photosynthesize, so it's on a short list of animals with such power.

I designed the whole campaign around a character I based off one of my favorite animals. Elyse was an Aasimar Cleric in flowing green robes that loved to steal artifacts of power and use them for herself. She was based off of a sea slug, Elysia chlorotica. https://t.co/gV6c6gixXW

I just finished my first #dnd5e campaign I ever DM'd this weekend! Real life blows and I hate it here, I will share the fantasy world I created instead! The campaign lasted over a year and we played 20 sessions total. We had to end early, but c'est la adulthood! 1/12 https://t.co/CmQJ103wMO

Anyone with a PhD in genetics, genomics, CS, statistics or a related field can apply from any country. Our working language is English and you'd be based @emblebi, just south of Cambridge on @WGCengage Campus.

You will join my small but perfectly formed research group, co-run by @tomaswfitz; we have a passion for understanding biology using outbred genetics, with both human and Medaka fish as our go-to species. We're a eclectic, open, fun team embedded in the great @emblebi

And there is also a similar postdoc position to work on genotype vs environmental toxin effects, again in Medaka fish, working with labs in @WHOI in Massachusetts and @DukeU in North Carolina in the US. Want to experience both sides of the atlantic?

Got a genetics, genomics, computer science or statistics degree? Want to do a postdoc on the genetics of individual variation o (on Medaka fish)? Want to work with myself and @tomaswfitz with @WittbrodtLab  in Heidelberg, ERC funded. Apply now! https://t.co/OpE9bR7qDw

Herd immunity is largely misunderstood including by many scientists. Acknowledging its existence does not imply letting COVID19 'rip through the population'. Conversely, denying 'herd immunity' is akin to drawing plans for a big bridge whilst dismissing gravity.3/

Herd immunity is what keeps >200 respiratory viruses in check and makes influenza pandemic lineages (e.g. 1918, 1957, 1968, 2009) go endemic. Reaching community immunisation primarily through vaccination can reduce morbidity and mortality significantly.2/

Herd immunity (community immunity) is not a strategy. It is the process describing that not everyone in the population needs to be immunised before an epidemic recedes. It is at the heart of any vaccination campaign, as vaccines are generally not indicated for everyone.1/ https://t.co/QdDpQsRz3X

A couple of decades of this kind of research has basically revealed that if you are not a middle of the road, middle of the educational spectrum, middle income, middle opinions person, you are more likely to be suspicious of vaccines.  The further you get from the middle....

For instance, we know that having little education makes you vaccine hesitant, but paradoxically so does having a lot of education (PhD level etc).  Likewise, if you are poor you are more likely to be unvaccinated, but we also see this in the very rich.

From these studies, we can often make statements like "Group X are 80% likely to be vaccinated whereas Group Y are only 40%".  Much of this is solid data and makes very interesting reading, but the cumulative result of hundreds of studies of this kind, has been very confusing.

A lot of effort has been spent over the years trying to find the predisposing factor to #VaccineHesitancy.  Many of the studies have methodologies related to focus groups or political polling - collect some volunteers from a particular category and ask them what they think.

Students don‚Äôt have eternity to learn the most eco-friendly solution, they need to graduate in a reasonable time. When countries and multinational companies are causing far more CO2 emissions, it seems unhelpful to pin this responsibility on students in a small research project.

This misses a crucial 3rd variable: the human-time to write the code. You will often have a result faster in R or Python than the time it takes to optimise a solution in a compiled language. Help us prevent disease in all people (and not just majority ancestry groups).  Join research studies.  Donate your DNA to help others (which will especially help others from your own ancestry) 5/6
We also can't do a good job of predicting and preventing disease in minority ancestry groups if we haven't recruited these individuals for research.  4/6

But we can't study diseases present in minority ancestry groups if we don't recruit research participants who have these diseases.  And we also need to study people without these diseases for comparison.  3/6

Most importantly, if there is an error in the analysis, that's also tricky. There is room to point out an error, but with caution and without brutal takedowns, especially of another trainee. If it's a trivial error, that's best left for an e-mail or over a beer. If it's major
If you think there is a caveat for interpreting the data, probably fair game to ask about. Maybe your assumption was wrong.
If you're serious about the extension being a collaboration, an e-mail about it has more meat on the bone.

- Asking about an extension of the method is tricky. Are you just showing off that you can come up with an experiment (guilty!)? Are you just really excited about the subject (also guilty!)? Is it an obvious extension? Ideas are easy to come by, but not execution.

- Generally, good:    - questions that are of broad interest     - clarification on a slide is /really/ good. Probably a lot of other people have the same question.   - ramifications of the work (good for a trainee to know their work is going somewhere)

If you want to dig into the plots and data in the paper, we have a little dashboard with lots of interactive stuff you can play with, available at https://t.co/PyzoItsZPm 22/n

Also thanks to @altmetric for making their data available free of charge, @richabdill and @blekhman for the https://t.co/MBfprA7lkF API, and the Harris lab for their feedback over the last several months. 21/n

Thanks to @DocEdge85, @Graham_Coop, @jgschraiber, and @jrossibarra for their comments on an early draft of the paper, and thanks especially to @E_BeyersCarlson, whose topic modeling dissertation chapter with @syardi was a huge inspiration for planting this idea in my head. 20/n

I hope our study starts conversations among scientists about what our social media presence can and cannot accomplish, and how we can document and share our research in a way that maximizes public scientific literacy and reduces potential harm. 19/n
In short, most of us are completely failing to use social media as a mechanism of positive outreach, and we are largely oblivious to the negative impacts of research shared openly on Twitter. 18/n

Sure, we have convinced ourselves that being active on Twitter equates to "outreach," but our study found that 96% of highly-tweeted preprints have majority academic audiences, suggesting very few papers ever penetrate the public mindset 17/n

As a community, academia still doesn't know what to do with social media. In many ways, #ScienceTwitter is just a digital extension of the ivory tower, oblivious and impenetrable to "outsiders" seeking to engage with our work. 16/n

In extreme cases, over half of the tweets about a given article come from users with much higher than average association with white nationalist networks, giving concrete evidence that science cannot be decoupled from the political environment in which it is carried out. 15/n https://t.co/849ycxGTQr

What's troubling is that, on a platform celebrated by scientists for providing unprecedented access to lay audiences and making "scicommers" out of us all, these bad actors have the potential to completely dominate the online conversations surrounding our work. 14/n

In fact, we find 10% of the preprints analyzed had sizable (>5% of the total) audience sectors associated with white nationalist communities. Several colleagues have expressed that this isn't (or shouldn't be) surprising, and perhaps they're right! 13/n

This gives us a fresh perspective on how we interpret impact, at least among online social networks‚Äîin some cases it might reveal new opportunities for interdisciplinary collaboration, but in others we might discover uncomfortable patterns of political misappropriation. 12/n

I see grant proposals as lottery tickets. If I need funding, I spend (put in the late nights) to buy lots of tickets. Often, the proposals I think are a long shot get funded and the proposals I think have a great chance get rejected.

My success rate is low and I'm not some sort of grant savant, but I hope my experience helps someone else. Further, @WyoWeeds is a pro. I'm sure he did these things and still ended up at the mercy of a very imperfect process.

4) I am a big fan of resubmissions. But, I would only do this if you are passionate about the project. I have given up on proposals, especial early in my career as my group moved in different directions.

3) Have lots of people read it. If it is a resubmission, provide the readers with the old reviews. This is hard to do with a new submission, but a resubmission opens up an entire year to get feedback.

Further, because of the culture of the panel, I had to frame my very observational study in terms of hypothesis driven research. This was hard, but brain storming with colleagues in my division helped.
... and I wasn't using those methods. So, even though it didn't make sense to me, I had to remove that phrase from the proposal.

2) Find someone who has served on a review panel in that section. Sometimes, in well-established sections, a sort of culture forms for what they expect. In my case I was using a certain phrase from the RFA. In the panel's mind that meant a certain type of assay was being used...

1) Talk to the program officer. Why? If for no other reason than they know you are serious and committed to getting the grant funded. However, they may be able to tell you things on the phone that didn't make it into the review summary.

This may be the most reliable study on #COVID19 sequelae  to date, insofar it has an acceptable control group and is based on non-subjective physical measurements. Though, it remains somewhat unsatisfactory. Better, larger and well-controlled studies are urgently needed.(5/5)

As such the decrease in aerobic capacity in the symptomatic group is likely a mix of genuine short- and possibly medium/long-term lung damage, but also a consequence of those ill with #COVID19 not getting as much physical exercise.(4/5)

The statistically significant decrease in aerobic capacity in symptomatic #COVID19 patients is not straightforward to interpret. During military training, fitness is expected to increase, which, as expected, was observed in ~10% of the unaffected/asymptomatic recruits.(3/5)

This is a fairly homogeneous cohort of ~200 18-27 year olds (~13% women). Conscription is mandatory for men in Switzerland, and this represents a fairly random sample of healthy young adults. It suggests that asymptomatic #COVID19 leads to no significant side-effects.(2/5) https://t.co/6RiqrzNzZ1

The extent to which #COVID19 can cause sequelae is a critical question. So in short. For fermented carrots we found that:1) Fermentation is really good for outcompeting nasty pathogens but please ferment long enough2)  Mixing with unpasteurised juices later can be a risk!

We found that storage of mixed juices under refrigeration cannot be relied upon as a safety measure ‚õîÔ∏è. It is recommended to use pasteurised juices for addition to the fermented juice, to reduce the likelihood of exposure to food borne pathogens.

And what if you want to mix your ferment with another freshly juiced vegetable, like cucumberü•í juice?Good idea, it tastes nice. But be aware, if your cucumber juice would be contaminated with pathogens, and you mix it with the fermented juice, your protective effect is gone.

Yes they are! ‚úÖIf you add food pathogens prior to the fermentation, they start to grow at the beginning, but get completely wiped out after at least 9 days of fermentation. ‚û°Ô∏è Good news, but please ferment long enough to make sure all bad boys are gone.

This makes it a good model system! More about that in one of my main PhD articles:https://t.co/2gXikPLAGO@vanbeeckw continued this work and wondered whether these fermentations are also good at keeping food-borne pathogens ‚ò£Ô∏è away if they are added to the fermentation?

At the @SarahLebeer lab we really like spontaneous carrot juice fermentations, because they are easy to set up and to maintain. Moreover, even without addition of a starter culture they are fairly repeatable, meaning that in every fermentation a very similar community emerges. https://t.co/z1AmrvLw6O

In the case of "Black Lives Matter", this is understandable. Engaging seriously with the moral question would risk:1) acknowledging the stated aims of the movement, and2) taking stock of the material consequences of BLM so far for disadvantaged black Americans.

A final plea, as ever. We are in this together - across the UK, but in fact, zooming out, worldwide. This is a humans vs virus struggle. We need to stay focused on suppressing the virus until the vaccines come.

Ultimately reality is far messier than this to be simple criteria, and really it is a "high risk of uncontrolled community transmission" judgement call but I personally think more discussion of this will provide more community understanding of where each region is.

The third is triggers - local and national. We need to have a better sense of when things need to be moved in regionally and nationally. This again has been happening in summer (Leicester, Bolton, Tyneside, Manchester...).

The second is ensuring things work; there is a huge difference between plans and reality, and reality has all the complications of society - things such as people with lower pay find it far harder to isolate; how digital access is uneven across jobs etc.

The tendency though is to ignore the risk to transmission side. There is little point in arguing about things that don't change substantially the risk of transmission; we've got to discuss the things which are high transmission environments (indoors, low ventilation, many people)

This has been somewhat discussed but it would be good to lay it out; the risk side is more well known than March and apolitical; the "importance to society" is very political and one can't really dodge that.

So - what are the questions we should be asking? The first is what is the arsenal of more responses beyond the ones rolling in. Here one needs prioritisation both by likely impact on transmission (pubs and clubs, sorry!) and importance to society (other NHS work, schools ++)

We need good monitoring (UK is pretty good actually here, in particular the ONS survey and deep testing) and good decision making if the trajectory is being held (and good decision making if the trajectory is bending back). Passive decision making is bad.

(it's valid, but a different argument, about whether more of this should be in place before the start of September. Obviously it would be better if it had; it is also far far harder to operationalise these things than most people realise. For a different thread.)

Decisions / changes now effect hospitalisation rates in 4-6weeks (longer) time; conversely the hospitalisation rates now are due to decisions 4 to 6 weeks ago. The doubling rate is lower than Feb/March (some stuff is working!) so we have time, but not oodles of time.

However, I'm extremely concerned that once information gets out about how bad the side effects can be, especially after the 2nd shot, the anti-vaxxers are going to be all over this.
Is it still worth getting the vaccine? Absolutely, if it works, since you may save your life and/or the lives of others, and since we NEED a vaccine to work for life to get back to normal.
There definitely had to have been an immune response, since the immune reaction after the 2nd shot was so much more severe than after the 1st shot.

I tested my antibodies using Quest serology, a month after the 1st shot. The results came back negative, which was surprising, since I had mild symptoms after the 1st shot (mild fever mostly), so I was sure I didn't get the placebo. Maybe Quest is looking at different antibodies?

After a very rough night, I am back to normal.I'm obviously an isolated case, but since all indications point to this vaccine being approved, I feel like people should know that the side effects may be severe, especially after the second shot.

Obviously it's not a live vaccine so it's not COVID, just a comparable immune response. Didn't sleep all night, had to ice my forehead all night long. SpO2 dropped from 98%->82%; heart rate increased 80->90+ over 4 hours; temp was over 38 deg C for 5 hours.

Maybe this is down to sample size, maybe it's down to selection bias (they only run screens in super long yardage), maybe it's opposition but I don't think it's arguable that they should probably try doing more of it.@benbbaldwin @cmikesspinmove and assorted nerds, Enjoy.

Now we come to the impetus for this whole spiel.. Seattle replacing early down runs with screens is an obviously smart decision. They produce far more on early downs and are clearly more likely to get a big play. https://t.co/UwfrM99cdY

Green Bay follows a similar trend as the other teams though the upside plays in the 10-25 *appears* more muted than the others. (Will need to find a better way of quantifying this) https://t.co/2Arl0E9SWA

KC  doesn't produce as much in the run game but the screen game is consistently slightly more productive than a typical run. That 4th down production is quite curious though. (Small samples) https://t.co/BoJcC5AFoW

LA have an interesting screen game and it seems to be pretty productive in general but their run game is clearly capable of producing useful yardage hence the "flatter" peak in their run plays. Even on 3rd down, their screens will outgain their runs. https://t.co/kIRM07ylyV
The obvious confounder here are team/talent effects right? So what about a few interesting teams? Seattle, LAR, KC & GB.

The difference in mean outcome gets smaller as you get closer to 3rd down. This may potentially be due to the number of yards to go but I don't have time to dig into that just yet but it's obvious that a bigger play is more likely with a screen pass than a run. https://t.co/kqwglfOx3L

Across all downs, the mediean run will gain you the same as the median screen pass but there's more likelihood of a big play with a screen and a higher probability of an actual gain with a run.. Pretty much nailed on gain vs dice roll. https://t.co/mhK2ODBgRN

Understanding conceptually what your code is doing and making sure it can be reused later is more important. A language is a means to an end, a way to communicate with a set of tools. Learning a new one could lead to new opportunities but will take hard work.

What really matters is reproducible results. Let‚Äôs stop with the petty rivalries that serve only to confuse new coders.If you document your code so that others can call and use it, no matter what language it‚Äôs in, they will thank you later. That includes your future self.

What should I learn? You‚Äôll get more help if others in your field use it.Using anything is fine if it works and gets things done.Ancient language that still works as you expect? Sure get it done.New trendy language that does cool things? Great! Learn as you go.

I‚Äôve worked with people who use R, Perl, Python, Julia, JavaScript, Rust, Ruby, MATLAB, Wolfram, C, C++, and Fortran.What‚Äôs the best language? Honestly it doesn‚Äôt matter, use whatever you want so long as you get the job done.

It's genuinely horrifying that the overtime in some research labs make Japanese companies look good in comparison. No one should be expected to sacrifice this much, especially not our best and brightest.

Of course, all researchers have deadlines from time-to-time but it should be your choice how far beyond the 9-5 you are willing to go. It is important to manage your time and workload carefully. Don't burn out or make foolish mistakes. Good ideas never come from this.

Also make sure to talk to people in labs when you're applying to join them. All applicants to our lab are given an opportunity to speak freely to lab members in confidence about our working environment. I think this is a great idea, you deserve to know what you're signing up for.

Hey students and ECRs, now is a good time to see what your future boss could be posting. It's that semi-regular time when everyone sounds off on academic working hours. Pay attention to who will respect your work-life balance, family commitments, health, or legal rights.

But what's even more problematic is the lack of funding and effort to understand the role racism has played in COVID outcomes. Socioeconomic disparities and lack of access  to care due to racist policies are known to affect health outcomes.

So this paper is methodologically unsound because the genetic differences within each self identified "racial" group could be as different as between groups. Because race is not biological.  This paper shouldn't even be written.

Differences in genetic ancestry can affect differences in gene expression.  You would need to actually genotype or sequence people and pair that information with differences in gene expression.  Then you could say "people with this genetic variant are at higher or lower risk".

When you take a group of people of the same "race" and look at their genetics, it's incredibly diverse because again, race as a social construct is not capturing underlying biology, genetic ancestry.  Race isn't biological.

One of the mistakes of my early training was conflating race and genetics. This is still done at every level of medicine and science. Race is a SOCIAL construct. It is not based on biology.  Race is not a risk factor; racism is.

We must react to terrorism by drawing blood, but never allow ourselves to become bloodthirsty.  We are better than that.  We are Americans.
And this is the end game of terrorism.  To instill fear into the hearts of their enemies, to turn brother against brother, and in the end, to create monsters like themselves.
It was a narrow ledge to walk, and we, as a nation, to this day, still are torn between reactive vengeance and proactive love.

In the subsequent days and years, our leaders tried to strike a balance between justice and compassion, wishing to deliver punishment that would deter future attacks, without descending into the depths of depravity that motivated the attackers.

The trip home was largely uneventful, and we arrived a day sooner than did those who waited at the hotel for the airlines to re-open.  But a huge psychological wound had been created in the national psyche, and we were forever changed.
Many of us had friends and colleagues from the middle east, who could easily be be mistaken for a "dangerous brown person" and so we worried about their safety as well as our own.
We knew this was going to cause an enormous backlash, and we all prayed for both sensitivity and specificity of the oncoming storm.

Back on the road, we would listen to news reports on the car radio, and then, when it became too emotional to handle, would turn it off and drive for hrs in silence, processing how the world had just changed.
Every mom and pop gas station that we visited had small groups of people huddled around a TV trying to gain information and perspective, on what was going on.
It was an eery trip. The skies were empty, and the radio full of people discussing, trying to come to grips with what had happened.

By risk-stratifying populations based on their individual, hereditary risk, multi-cancer, earlier detection companies could materially improve economics, patient outcomes, and test performance.

Moreover, hereditary cancer testing, which can be very cheap based on who you order from, need only be done once. Low risk persons can be tested later in life, less frequently, or not at all. High risk persons can be tested earlier or more often.

However, age isn't the only variable affecting cancer risk. Hereditary cancer testing, which is based on your individual predisposition to cancer(s) as determined by mutations you inherited (e.g. TP53, BRCA1/2, etc.), is a HUGE determinant of cancer risk.

By incidence rate, I'm referring to the number of persons in a group that is diagnosed with cancer. Intuitively, screening 100,000 people aged 65+ will result in better outcomes and economics than screening 100,000 teenagers. Why?Cancer incidence increases with age.

Hot Take (üî•):It's unwise for multi-cancer, earlier detection companies to deploy large-scale screening programs without upfront, hereditary cancer testing. The most important input variable for large-scale screening is the incidence rate of cancer in the population.

So by eating a "bad" bacteria, then signaling from the gut to germline to neurons to avoid it in the future, their progeny inherit a "memory" of a (potentially) stressful event - giving us a good reason for TEI to exist. @OdedRechavi  @MCHammer

This system is a nice way for worms to change their behavior - from attraction to avoidance - of a ubiquitous bacteria that can switch from food to pathogen, dep. on temp - but then resume normal attraction later.

So we think that worms can ‚Äúread‚Äù small RNAs from pathogenic bacteria and use that information to induce a rapid avoidance response that can be inherited, but can also be turned off eventually, when it's possible that the bacteria is no longer pathogenic (e.g., at lower temps)
This pathway uses the RNAi machinery in the intestine, piRNAs and P granules in the germline, and this down-regulates a gene called maco-1 in the ASI neuron, which is critical for learned avoidance.

For PA14, just one small RNA called P11 is sufficient to induce the whole effect, which amazed us - and instantly led to the question of whether there is a "matching" target gene - there is: maco-1, a neuronal gene - and it affects pathogen avoidance.

These worms were NEVER SICK! They just act like they had been,like they were vaccinated against PA14. By transferring the pathogenic bacteria's small RNAs (that signal that the bacteria are pathogenic), the worms know to avoid them - and pass it on to help their progeny survive
We purified the small RNAs from pathogenic bacteria, & when we put it on lab E. coli ‚Äì it "taught" the worms to avoid PA14 without ever encountering them!
We started to wonder how worms make this distinction ‚Äì what is it about PA14 that the worms recognize to induce this effect? We wondered, what if the worms could ‚Äúread‚Äù the bacteria somehow?

You might remember that we found that C. elegans  exposed to pathogenic Pseudomonas PA14 not only avoided the bacteria when it met it again, but also passed on this learned avoidance to its progeny for four generations (Moore et al. Cell 2019)
...we show that worms can ‚Äúread‚Äù the small RNAs that bacteria make when they are pathogenic, using a new type of trans-kingdom signaling.

Ever wonder what transgenerational epigenetic inheritance (TEI) is good for? (Yes, what‚Äôs the #PhysiologicalRelevance?) We showed earlier that worms can learn to avoid pathogens, and use TEI to pass on this memory for a few generations. In our new paper....https://t.co/oU9P6kBFCq

8/8In summary, we'll dive into long-reads, prognostics, and other ways to tackle overtreatment throughout the week. Please add any and all questions and I'll try to address them in my weekly newsletter.

7/8While her work utilized low pass short-reads, I'll note that copy number variants (CNVs) are particularly amenable to long-read platforms (so long as tissue isn't degraded). Here's another great paper by @mike_schatz and team that discusses this: https://t.co/50IVgJUJX3

6/8I still need to go in depth, but I was really excited by this paper (https://t.co/2ku8pqCNxk) published in Nature by @RFitzgerald_lab. She summarizes much better than I could, so I'll direct readers to her thread:https://t.co/gLnhBylZCT

5/8Molecular prognostic tests result from the collision of #MachineLearning and next-gen sequencing, both of which rapidly are becoming cheaper. We think that these tests, even if given annually for decades, should be considerably cheaper than the cost of cancer treatment.

4/8We believe molecular prognostic testing could give physicians a better understanding of a tumor's eventual fate, perhaps reducing the risk of overtreatment. This approach is not a panacea, and there's still much learning to do, but the future looks bright.

3/8Companies like Veracyte (VCYT) and Castle (CSTL) offer prognostic tests, using a combination of machine learning and gene expression, to risk-stratify suspicious nodules beyond standard cytopathology. https://t.co/aGw9N4kU5Whttps://t.co/Dury9SRx6d

2/8We believe multi-cancer liquid biopsy screening will allow dozens of cancers to be detected earlier. However, not all tumors are lethal. Some may never cause symptoms. By reflexing to surgery, we risk overtreating patients whose tumors may never need it.

Memory fences will also ensure that you do not read outdated data due to per-core caching. Standard library atomic types (which provide a nice API over this + some CAS operations) are usually the fastest option, compared to locks or other higher-level constructs.

Memory fences are your best friend. Consider the task of building a struct then setting a finished building flag. Use a "release" memory fence to guarantee that the flag is set only after the struct is fully initialized, before accessing in another thread with an "acquire" fence.

Daily reminder that the order your code appears in your editor likely will *not* be the execution order. Your compiler and your CPU will reorder your code, which is totally fine for single-core programming, but a nightmare when synchronizing across multiple cores.

There are now consistent noises of readouts for the vaccine results later this autumn (some partly politically driven in a slightly depressing way) but some vaccines probably will have reasonable data then. BUT >>

The development of vaccines have gone far far faster than anyone expected (I have been on a Phase II/III trial for the Oxford vaccine since the summer); more vaccines are being made and at a faster rate than ever expected.

Q: So - is there a plan?A: Broadly yes, though one does have to piece it together. The main plan in most European countries, UK included, is have enough control of viral transmission until there is a good enough vaccine for the at risk (elderly) population.
Q: This is not going to work well when it is rainingA: Agreed

Q: So we shouldn't go to pubs? Or clubs?A: Beer gardens / outside seem fine. Inside - keep the windows open, wash everything obsessively and get back outside. Personally I think it's just best not to go to clubs.

The main concern though is that schools and universities going back means lots of potential new and more contact patterns - basically, teenagers + young adults going to pubs and clubs, adults going work place + pubs. More contacts, more at risky locations

Q: Why are people so concerned about schools reopening?A: Partly I think it is the unknown and genuine concern, I think unfounded, for risk to children. Partly it is the risk for the staff (though the evidence is thin that teaching staff are more at risk); however >>

Q: Is there any risk to my children?A: It is low, and it was low in the holidays when your children were somewhere else (likely ... having ice creams, visiting seaside cafes etc). Children need education and peers - they will be happier and safe in schools.

Q: Will schools going back increase transmission?A: We don't know. What we do know is that schools going back is also a big shift in contact patterns post holidays - people moving around, more workplace visits, different visits by different people. It is not just about schools.
France the cases have climbed but the hospitalisations have just nudged up. Belgium had a mini 2nd wave outbreak which they tamed by reintroducing local lockdowns and more mask wearing.

Q: So - should I get worried about my friend in Madrid? Or Lyon? Or Sevilla? Other places in Europe?A: If they are young, likely not. If they are old... then location matters. Spain has strong growth of cases and hospitalisation rates have climbed, in particular in Madrid >>

Sweden's strategy is more nuanced than the headlines make out elsewhere. There was early on a higher acceptance of natural progression of the virus, but in many ways Sweden has ended up in a similar place to much of Europe - low viral transmission due to behavioural changes
If we did this at the virus' natural rate it would mean the health systems would have to become dedicated to palliative care for many months as well as just a large number of people dying. >>

Q: What about just letting everyone have it at some controlled rate now? Isn't this what Sweden is doing?A: Just letting the virus circulate will mean somewhere around 0.5% (perhaps a little lower) of people dying and many more people having a debilitating disease >>

To make a segregation work to be confident that you just let rip in one part of the population without infecting another part you really have to have basically no contact - anywhere, any context, any shop, any school, any hospital and any family. It's basically unfeasible.

Q: OK. Can't we just let the young people get it, and then they will all be immuneA: Although the rate is higher in the young it is still in the 1 in 1,000 or so (say in France) - there is plenty further it can get to and at some point it will likely go into the older population

So, MR and PR are additive in their effects on overall hereditary disease risk. Therefore, including PRS for monogenic risk carriers may meaningfully alter the results of a monogenic risk test for Tier 1 conditions, and likely more over time.

A higher odds ratio (y-axis, left chart) means the more likely the person develops the disease in question. The right chart includes age-at-diagnosis. Interestingly, a very low PRS can be benevolent, rescuing the risk imparted by a dangerous monogenic variant to near baseline.

The study showed that the risk imparted by dangerous, monogenic variants could be meaningfully altered by assessing the polygenic background. One recent (and rigorous) study (Fahed et al.) showed how the combination of monogenic risk (MR) and polygenic risk (PR) could be assessed in parallel. I'm going to summarize the authors' findings and then what I think this means for molecular diagnostic companies.

There's a lack of standardization for PRS algorithms or which genes/variants to include in the predictive model. Finally, as I alluded to earlier, the odds ratios for many standalone PRSs is low(er), making them harder for doctors to interpret.

Importantly, PRSs have weaker predictive power for non-Europeans since the majority of training data was conducted on Europeans. PRSs don't have the same level of evidence, transparency, or curation. The functional connectivity between variant(s) and diseases is more obscure.

Individually, these variants may not mean much, but in aggregate, they could be a powerful signal to predict the penetrance of disease from a patient's genotype. PRSs have been widely used in research settings, but have struggled to gain traction clinically. Why?
